<font color="#FF0000">MONTE GRAPPA</font><br>
<tt>Mon Sep  8  6:19:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art,<br><br>
I toured the countryside of Northern Italy three years ago. Spent the day on a mountain called Monte Grappa - the scene of a siege type battle between Austria and Italy - during WWI.<br><br>
Since I was with other people it had not really been my intention to visit there. My brother in law hang glides and he and others used the mountain for take offs. I didn't know the significance or that a great battle had been staged  until I realized that the place where we were taking our picnic seemed strangely familiar. It had been levelled off and bordered with rocks. I looked nearby  and saw a couple more places just like our picnic spot - we were in the middle of a fairly well preserved area that had been an artillery or mortar section - complete with small ammo bunkers.<br><br>
It seemed sacreligious to me - for us to be laughing and eating - not seeming to care about the sanctity of the mountain where many had known real suffering so many years ago. Hallowed ground.<br><br>
I walked to the top of the mountain where there was constructed a giant memorial with plaques. Each soldier who had fallen during the siege of Monte Grappa was named on a plaque. The memorial had been erected and dedicated by Benito Mussolini in the 1930's. A much smaller memorial, a bit further down the hill, commemorated the fall of the Fascisti during WWII.<br><br>
I spent the day away from my wife, her sister and her sister's husband. I didn't want to provide a burden for the rest. Besides they would never understand. Hiking and searching. I could barely speak because of my heavy heart.  <br><br>
The flashback to my own time of war was ominous. The sounds of the firefight. The terrifying feeling of hugging the ground - not knowing if the incoming mortars - which were going to land SOMEWHERE - would seek out my part of the landscape. The shouts, the curses, and the smells. It all came back to me up on that mountain in that foreign land.<br><br>
My sadness turned to awe when I realized that I shared a common bond with those who fought on Monte Grappa. <br><br>
Those of us who return from battles and who comprise the ranks of the &quot;Universal Soldier&quot; never fail to say words like, &quot;never again&quot; or &quot;no more war.&quot; These words played in my mind over and over again.<br><br>

